In Spring Boot, the common REST API HTTP methods are:

GET → Read/fetch data
POST → Create new data
PUT → Update existing data (usually full update)
DELETE → Remove data

These are the main CRUD operations:

Operation    HTTP Method    Example
Create       POST           Add a new user
Read         GET            Fetch user details
Update       PUT            Update user info
Delete       DELETE         Remove a user

Example in Spring Boot:

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/users")
public class UserController {

    @GetMapping
    public String getUsers() {
        return "Get Users";
    }

    @PostMapping
    public String createUser() {
        return "Create User";
    }

    @PutMapping("/{id}")
    public String updateUser(@PathVariable int id) {
        return "Update User " + id;
    }

    @DeleteMapping("/{id}")
    public String deleteUser(@PathVariable int id) {
        return "Delete User " + id;
    }
}

There are also other HTTP methods sometimes used:

PATCH → Partial update
OPTIONS → Supported methods info
HEAD → Like GET but without body

But for most Spring Boot REST APIs, the main four are GET, POST, PUT, and DELETE.
